SIMPLE: worry
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Worry
<hw>Wor"ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Worried</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Worrying</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>worowen</ets>,
<ets>wirien</ets>, to strangle, AS. <ets>wyrgan</ets> in
<ets>⟦amac⟧wyrgan</ets>; akin to D. <ets>worgen</ets>,
<ets>wurgen</ets>, to strangle, OHG. <ets>wurgen</ets>, G.
<ets>w⟦uum⟧rgen</ets>, Lith. <ets>verszti</ets>, and perhaps to E.
<ets>wring</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To harass by pursuit and barking; to attack
repeatedly; also, to tear or mangle with the teeth.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A hellhound that doth hunt us all to death;⟦br⟧
That dog that had his teeth before his eyes,⟦br⟧
To <qex>worry</qex> lambs and lap their gentle blood.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To harass or beset with importunity, or with care an
anxiety; to vex; to annoy; to torment; to tease; to fret; to trouble; to
plague.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧A church <xex>worried</xex> with
reformation.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>South.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let them rail,⟦br⟧
And <qex>worry</qex> one another at their pleasure.</q>
<rj><qau>Rowe.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Worry</qex> him out till he gives consent.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To harass with labor; to fatigue.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Worry</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Worry
<hw>Wor"ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To feel or express
undue care and anxiety; to manifest disquietude or pain; to be fretful;
to chafe; <as>as, the child <ex>worries</ex>; the horse
<ex>worries</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Worry</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Worry
<hw>Wor"ry</hw>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Worries</plw>
<pr>(<?/)</pr>.</plu> <def>A state of undue solicitude; a state of
disturbance from care and anxiety; vexation; anxiety; fret; <as>as, to
be in a <ex>worry</ex></as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The whir and <xex>worry</xex>
of spindle and of loom.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Sir T. Browne.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Worryingly</ent>⟦br⟧
